post_text: As we continue to work on streamlining things for the upcoming Curbside Meals Pick Up program this Saturday, we would like to remind everyone to please wear a mask, and if possible pop your trunk or hatchback to make handing over the meals go a little smoother. This program is available to any child 18 and under. If children are not in the vehicle, proof of the children in the household must be shown. This can include things like, the meals barcodes, birth certificates, recent report cards, WIC card, most recent student ID, etc.

post_text:
District teachers honored by Region One ESC
The two Mission Consolidated Independent School District (CISD) District Teachers of the Year were honored this evening by Region One Education Service Center (ESC). It was a part of the Region One Teacher of the Year virtual recognition. During the event, each District Teacher of the Year from throughout the Region One area is recognized and the regional teachers of the year announced.
Pictured are the Mission CISD District Teachers of the Year recognitions from the virtual event. The Mission CISD Secondary Teacher of the Year is Joselito Guanzon from Mission High School. The Mission CISD Elementary Teacher of the Year is Rebecca Munguia from Bryan Elementary School. We are proud of you both!!

Pictured are the Mission CISD District Teachers of the Year recognitions from the virtual event. The Mission CISD Secondary Teacher of the Year is Joselito Guanzon from Mission High School. The Mission CISD Elementary Teacher of the Year is Rebecca Munguia from Bryan Elementary School. We are proud of you both!!

post_text: The interior transformation of the old Lacks building into the Mission CISD Annex is well underway, led by our maintenance department. Still lots to do, but it is starting to take shape. Just one of many projects underway.

post_text: Our apologies as many of our page posts were hit with a large spam attack with bogus links for viewing the parent conference sessions. The only app some of you may need to download if viewing through a smartphone or tablet is the Microsoft Teams app, and the official links you received from the district would prompt you for that if needed. Our efforts to control the spam attack on comments may also result in some of your comments not being visible. It is unfortunate the step was necessary in this case and is the first time in over ten years we have had to take steps like that.
text: Our apologies as many of our page posts were hit with a large spam attack with bogus links for viewing the parent conference sessions. The only app some of you may need to download if viewing through a smartphone or tablet is the Microsoft Teams app, and the official links you received from the district would prompt you for that if needed. If approved, the money will be paid directly to the funeral home. To apply visit www.hidalgocares.org/covidcondolenceprogram. You can also apply in person at Hidalgo County Health and Human Services offices: https://buff.ly/3ksifwF

Eligibility is based on the following:
üîπMust be a resident of Hidalgo County
üîπCause of death must be COVID-19 related
üîπMust be affected by COVID-19 due to loss of income
üîπIncome must be below 300% Federal Poverty Income Limits (more info: https://buff.ly/3gMdsUv )
üîπHousehold composition
üîπMust have signed quote or contract from the funeral home
üîπOther worksheet criteria

The following important message is going out to all parents this evening through our mass notification system.
Dear Parents,
Your assistance is needed in revising the Preference in Delivery of Instruction and Remote Access Survey for 2020-2021 through the Parent Portal.

When parents log in to the Parent Portal, you will see a notice that stating ‚ÄúUnfinished Version Exists‚Äù. Please use the link ‚ÄúStart Over‚Äù to complete the survey. Please complete one survey per child.

In case you do not recall your username and password for the Parent Portal, you will be receiving an email with this information. If you need any assistance, please contact Information Systems at Info_Systems@mcisd.org. This is a very important survey to provide Mission CISD with information regarding the type of devices that your children may need for remote instruction.

If no changes are needed to devices or internet services, you do not need to update the survey. If changes in the devices and/or internet are needed, please log into the Parent Portal and complete the survey by July 22.

Thank you.

post_text: The Mission CISD Board of Trustees held an emergency meeting this afternoon to address concerns relating to a return to school during the COVID-19 pandemic. This included unanimous approval of a special resolution supporting greater authority for our County Judge, and outlining four main actionable items. A letter to County Judge Richard Cortez and the resolution is included in this post. Here is a link to a news release regarding today's development, https://www.mcisd.net/apps/news/article/1255025

post_text:
Commencement ceremonies start tomorrow! We are excited to be able to provide an in-person ceremony for the Classes of 2020. However, we all must follow certain rules set by the state in order to do it.
-Be sure to get the health forms done and turned in
-All attendees are encouraged to wear masks/face coverings
-All graduates will be provided with a mask to wear
-Follow all social distancing markers, and guidelines
-Follow all instructions of staff regarding seating and social distancing
-Hand sanitizer stations will be available
-No groups will be allowed to gather within the stadium gates before, during, or after the ceremonies
-No seated family groups larger than 5 people
-Follow directions on exiting the bleachers as that will be controlled by row to allow better social distancing standards to be maintained
-Water and juice will be available for purchase in the concession areas
-Our goal is to provide the best experience possible, while providing for the health and safety of all attendees.

The virus that causes COVID-19 can spread from a person before they have symptoms. Take action to slow the spread by wearing a cloth face covering in public spaces where you're likely to interact with others, keeping at least 6 feet of physical distance, and frequently washing your hands.

post_text: Veterans Memorial High School had two students, Damian Gonzalez and Juan Ramirez, competed in the Skills USA on February 21st in the category of Information Technology. Damian Gonzalez placed 1st earning him a spot at the Skills USA State competition slated for April 2-5. Juan Ramirez received 2nd place, earning him an opportunity to attend in Damian's place should he not be able to attend. Only the students that place 1st are the only ones that advance to State competition.

post_text: The Mission High School (MHS) boys powerlifting team has something new and shiny for the trophy case. They earned the District 30-6A championship this past weekend. The team members are (along with district tournament result): Gael Fernandez, third place; Michael Tamez, district champion; Mario Marquez, district champion; Leonardo Perez, second place; Ivan Chavez, fourth place; Gonzalo Perez, third place; Cristian Hernandez, district champion; Zeke Cuadros, fourth place; Houston Torres, third place; Steven Alvarez, second place; Fabian Ahumada; Gustavo Pedraza, manager.

post_text: Mission CISD elementary students exhibited their Science Fair projects at Ralph Cantu Jr. High on January 23, 2020. Students use research, analytical, and creativity skills in order to create fascinating and innovative projects. Participants must come up with an idea, run an experiment, and report their findings using data, graphs and a poster display. These students were up to the challenge and proudly spoke to the judges about their projects.

post_text: Mission CISD Migrant students attended a Youth Leadership Conference on January 13th for high school students and January 14th for middle school students at the Mission Events Center. The keynote speaker, Amanda Peryear, spoke about her challenges growing up and how overcoming those challenges has helped her pave her way to success. Peryear is a poet, ghost writer for music artists, and has published four books. Students were excited to hear from her since she is originally from the Rio Grande Valley but currently resides in Brooklyn, New York.

post_text:
Wow! Did you realize that Friday is our last school day of this decade?!
Oh. Also, don't forget it is an early release day for students and staff. On December 20, elementary schools will dismiss students at 11:30 a.m. Junior high, high school, and Options/Roosevelt Alternative students will dismiss at 12:30 p.m.
Central administrative offices will close at 1:30 p.m. on December 20.
